1
00:00:04,321 --> 00:00:06,201
DOCTOR: 7he Monks have been with us

2
00:00:06,601 --> 00:00:08,041
from the beginning.

3
00:00:09,641 --> 00:00:13,401
They shepherded humanity
through its formative years,

4
00:00:13,961 --> 00:00:15,601
gently guiding

5
00:00:15,801 --> 00:00:16,921
and encouraging.

6
00:00:17,801 --> 00:00:21,641
Like a parent clapping their hands
at a baby's first steps.

7
00:00:23,841 --> 00:00:26,361
They have been instrumental
in all the advances

8
00:00:26,441 --> 00:00:28,201
of culture and technology.

9
00:00:29,961 --> 00:00:31,561
They watched proudly

10
00:00:32,401 --> 00:00:35,201
as man invented the light bulb,

11
00:00:35,281 --> 00:00:38,361
the telephone and the Internet.

12
00:00:39,681 --> 00:00:43,881
They were even there to welcome
the first man on the moon.

13
00:00:44,201 --> 00:00:47,321
NEIL ARMSTRONG: (RECORDED VOICE)
That's one small step for man,

14
00:00:47,401 --> 00:00:49,721
one giant leap for mankind.

15
00:00:50,041 --> 00:00:52,601
DOCTOR: And they have
defended us, too.

16
00:00:52,681 --> 00:00:56,281
Who can forget the time
the Monks defeated the Daleks?

17
00:00:56,961 --> 00:00:59,201
The Cybermen, the Weeping Angels?

18
00:01:00,121 --> 00:01:05,761
Two species sharing a history
as happily as they share a planet.

19
00:01:05,841 --> 00:01:10,561
Humanity and the Monks are a blissful
and perfect partnership.

20
00:01:11,041 --> 00:01:12,841
How lucky Earth is

21
00:01:12,921 --> 00:01:16,161
to have an ally as powerful
and as tender

22
00:01:16,881 --> 00:01:18,121
as the Monks,

23
00:01:18,201 --> 00:01:21,001
that asks for nothing
in return for their benevolence

24
00:01:22,041 --> 00:01:24,441
-but obedience...
-(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

25
00:01:26,161 --> 00:01:28,001
(KNOCKING CONTINUES)

26
00:01:31,201 --> 00:01:32,361
SOLDIER 1: Go, go, go!

27
00:01:32,681 --> 00:01:33,681
Get down!

28
00:01:33,921 --> 00:01:35,841
On your knees. Hands on your heads!

29
00:01:35,921 --> 00:01:38,601
SOLDIER 2: Get down.
On your knees. Stay down!

30
00:01:39,001 --> 00:01:40,121
SOLDIER 1: Search the room!

31
00:01:50,001 --> 00:01:51,521
-Jane Bishop, you are charged with...
-Get off me!

32
00:01:51,601 --> 00:01:53,041
You are charged

33
00:01:53,361 --> 00:01:55,601
with the manufacture and possession
of propaganda

34
00:01:55,681 --> 00:01:58,081
intended to undermine the true history.

35
00:01:58,361 --> 00:02:02,121
This is in contravention
of the Memory Crimes Act of 1975.

36
00:02:02,201 --> 00:02:03,321
1975.

37
00:02:03,641 --> 00:02:05,641
The Monks have only been here
a few months...

38
00:02:05,721 --> 00:02:08,521
Therefore I sentence you to 10 years
in a lab our camp. Take her away.

39
00:02:08,601 --> 00:02:11,321
It's okay! Be a good boy for Mummy!

40
00:02:13,801 --> 00:02:15,761
The Monks have only been here
a few months.

41
00:02:16,681 --> 00:02:18,521
Fight back. It's all lies!

42
00:02:19,161 --> 00:02:20,161
SOLDIER: Get in.

43
00:02:20,281 --> 00:02:21,681
WOMAN: You know it's all lies.

44
00:02:25,321 --> 00:02:27,761
SOLDIER: All right. Nothing to see.
Move along.

45
00:02:28,001 --> 00:02:29,361
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

46
00:02:32,521 --> 00:02:34,641
(SIRENS WAILING)

47
00:02:50,921 --> 00:02:51,921
DOCTOR: So relax.

48
00:02:52,201 --> 00:02:53,321
Do as you're told.

49
00:02:54,161 --> 00:02:56,921
Your future is taken care of.

50
00:03:01,361 --> 00:03:03,361
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

51
00:03:55,881 --> 00:03:56,881
(SIGHS)

52
00:04:02,041 --> 00:04:03,641
(BREATHES RAPIDLY)

53
00:04:03,961 --> 00:04:06,321
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING OUTSIDE)

54
00:04:11,161 --> 00:04:12,201
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

55
00:04:23,601 --> 00:04:24,601
Hello, Mum.

56
00:04:28,721 --> 00:04:29,721
The Monks...

57
00:04:30,281 --> 00:04:31,281
(SIGHS)

58
00:04:33,681 --> 00:04:35,721
The Monks have only
been here for six months.

59
00:04:37,521 --> 00:04:39,601
BILL: 7 can't remember how
I escaped, Mum.

60
00:04:40,321 --> 00:04:41,921
I asked for their help and then...

61
00:04:42,801 --> 00:04:44,001
And then there's nothing.

62
00:04:45,441 --> 00:04:47,481
And then I woke up
and the Monks were here.

63
00:04:47,561 --> 00:04:49,081
And they'd always been here.

64
00:04:49,161 --> 00:04:50,281
SOLDIER: You. Come with me!

65
00:04:51,081 --> 00:04:53,641
BILL: Everything they told us,
all that we believe now

66
00:04:53,721 --> 00:04:54,761
is a lie.

67
00:04:58,801 --> 00:05:02,521
But I don't understand it
because no one's saying anything.

68
00:05:03,441 --> 00:05:05,601
It's like they've been...

69
00:05:05,721 --> 00:05:07,321
Like they've been brainwashed.

70
00:05:07,401 --> 00:05:10,161
PRESENTER: (ON TV)
...with those who would do them harm.

71
00:05:10,561 --> 00:05:13,841
By implementing
a swift and painless death.

72
00:05:14,161 --> 00:05:15,161
(ALL CHEER)

73
00:05:16,601 --> 00:05:18,721
Praise be the justice of the Monks.

74
00:05:19,281 --> 00:05:21,401
I travelled
with a man called the Doctor.

75
00:05:21,841 --> 00:05:24,281
And his friend, Nardole.
And I did this

76
00:05:24,681 --> 00:05:25,681
to save him.

77
00:05:25,801 --> 00:05:27,561
BILL: I'm trying to stay strong
without them

78
00:05:27,641 --> 00:05:29,961
but every day it's harder to remember
what's real any more.

79
00:05:30,361 --> 00:05:31,681
If you suspect a colleague,

80
00:05:32,161 --> 00:05:35,441
a neighbour or a family member
of being a memory criminal...

81
00:05:35,561 --> 00:05:37,441
BILL: And I know,
I know how it looks, Mum.

82
00:05:37,841 --> 00:05:39,881
With all of the stuff that
he's been saying on the telly,

83
00:05:40,481 --> 00:05:42,161
but it's all right.

84
00:05:43,401 --> 00:05:44,521
Because I know he has a plan.

85
00:05:45,961 --> 00:05:49,241
One day soon, he's gonna come back
and save us all.

86
00:05:50,401 --> 00:05:51,401
One day...

87
00:05:51,801 --> 00:05:53,001
(KEYS JANGLING)

88
00:06:06,081 --> 00:06:07,081
(DOOR CLOSING)

89
00:06:11,001 --> 00:06:12,961
(BOTH SCREAMING)

90
00:06:13,321 --> 00:06:16,001
What you doing?
It's me. Nardy!

91
00:06:16,201 --> 00:06:18,001
No. Wait. Shut up.
Tell me something.

92
00:06:18,521 --> 00:06:20,601
That first time,
with the Heather creature chasing us,

93
00:06:20,681 --> 00:06:21,721
where did we run away to?

94
00:06:21,841 --> 00:06:22,841
Australia.

95
00:06:23,281 --> 00:06:24,441
What noise do spaceship doors make?

96
00:06:24,841 --> 00:06:26,161
Shook, shook. Obviously.

97
00:06:28,121 --> 00:06:29,121
NARDOLE: Oh.

98
00:06:29,681 --> 00:06:30,921
BILL: Oh, God.

99
00:06:33,121 --> 00:06:35,521
It happened. I knew it.

100
00:06:35,921 --> 00:06:37,321
It all really happened.

101
00:06:38,401 --> 00:06:40,081
-Ow!
-Where have you been?

102
00:06:40,161 --> 00:06:42,561
-That hurt me. That really hurt me.
-I needed you.

103
00:06:42,641 --> 00:06:45,881
Well, I got contaminated
by that bacteria in the lab, didn't I?

104
00:06:45,961 --> 00:06:47,561
I was laid up for six weeks.

105
00:06:47,641 --> 00:06:49,321
If I was human, I would have died.

106
00:06:49,401 --> 00:06:50,881
Right now you'd be talking to...

107
00:06:51,641 --> 00:06:53,401
Come to think of it,
who were you talking to?

108
00:06:53,521 --> 00:06:54,521
Um, er...

109
00:06:55,641 --> 00:06:56,641
My...

110
00:06:57,081 --> 00:06:59,281
Uh, my, my mum.

111
00:06:59,961 --> 00:07:02,281
I thought your mum

112
00:07:02,361 --> 00:07:03,761
(SOFTLY) died.

113
00:07:03,841 --> 00:07:06,241
You know, when you were
(SOFTLY) little.

114
00:07:06,521 --> 00:07:08,841
I made up a version of her.

115
00:07:10,441 --> 00:07:11,881
Yeah, I talk to her all the time.

116
00:07:12,361 --> 00:07:13,361
Hmm.

117
00:07:14,041 --> 00:07:15,521
Oh, well, that's not that weird.

118
00:07:16,001 --> 00:07:18,161
Yeah, I used to have
an imaginary friend.

119
00:07:18,241 --> 00:07:19,721
Till he left me for someone else.

120
00:07:19,801 --> 00:07:21,241
(CHUCKLES) I know. Charming.

121
00:07:22,321 --> 00:07:23,921
They're doing something to us.

122
00:07:24,001 --> 00:07:25,681
The Monks. I can't think straight.

123
00:07:26,441 --> 00:07:28,481
It's like... They're saying
they've been here forever,

124
00:07:28,561 --> 00:07:29,961
and I know they haven't.

125
00:07:30,641 --> 00:07:33,081
But part of me is starting to think
that it's real.

126
00:07:33,921 --> 00:07:35,241
Every day I have to...

127
00:07:35,321 --> 00:07:36,601
I have to remind myself
that everything that

128
00:07:36,681 --> 00:07:39,001
you, me and the Doctor did
actually happened

129
00:07:39,081 --> 00:07:40,881
and it wasn't just a dream.

130
00:07:42,241 --> 00:07:43,241
Why do it?

131
00:07:43,881 --> 00:07:45,081
That's what I don't get.

132
00:07:45,961 --> 00:07:48,161
They invade somewhere, take control,

133
00:07:48,241 --> 00:07:50,481
why go to the trouble
of changing the past?

134
00:07:50,681 --> 00:07:52,001
However bad the situation is,

135
00:07:52,081 --> 00:07:54,001
if people think
that's how it's always been,

136
00:07:54,081 --> 00:07:56,641
they put up with it.
It's 90% of the job done.

137
00:07:57,041 --> 00:07:58,041
Wait.

138
00:07:58,961 --> 00:08:00,801
-You said you were ill for six weeks.
-Hmm?

139
00:08:01,001 --> 00:08:02,281
What you been doing since then?

140
00:08:02,801 --> 00:08:03,961
Looking for the Doctor.

141
00:08:04,041 --> 00:08:05,041
Have you found him?

142
00:08:05,481 --> 00:08:07,641
Well, let's just say...

143
00:08:10,161 --> 00:08:12,001
-Yes, yes, yes. I found him.
-(GASPS)

144
00:08:12,521 --> 00:08:13,521
So...

145
00:08:13,881 --> 00:08:16,001
All anyone's seen of the Doctor

146
00:08:16,281 --> 00:08:17,641
in the last six months

147
00:08:17,721 --> 00:08:19,241
are those broadcasts he does.

148
00:08:19,321 --> 00:08:21,281
He's faking it. I'm positive.

149
00:08:21,361 --> 00:08:22,561
He hasn't joined the Monks.

150
00:08:22,841 --> 00:08:26,001
He's being held prisoner. He's just...
He's just biding his time. Waiting.

151
00:08:26,281 --> 00:08:28,641
The thing is, the Monks have got
some kind of scrambler

152
00:08:28,721 --> 00:08:31,001
so no one can trace the broadcasts.

153
00:08:31,081 --> 00:08:34,001
Lucky then that I have got this!

154
00:08:34,081 --> 00:08:35,121
(WHIRRS)

155
00:08:35,201 --> 00:08:38,681
It traces the source of the signal
and gives a map coordinate.

156
00:08:39,001 --> 00:08:41,201
Cool. Where did you get it?

157
00:08:41,441 --> 00:08:42,841
Found it in the TARDIS.

158
00:08:42,921 --> 00:08:44,041
Yeah, it was in one of the drawers

159
00:08:44,121 --> 00:08:46,241
with some old takeaway menus
and 50 Danish Kroner.

160
00:08:46,601 --> 00:08:48,881
Anyway, this is them.

161
00:08:49,161 --> 00:08:50,721
-So he's at sea.
-Mmm-hmm.

162
00:08:51,281 --> 00:08:54,441
Yeah. Yeah, the Monks have gotten him
in one of the old prison boats.

163
00:08:54,521 --> 00:08:56,241
Hulks, they use to call them.

164
00:08:56,441 --> 00:08:57,521
So how do we get to him?

165
00:08:57,921 --> 00:09:00,241
Every six weeks,
all their food and fuel and stuff

166
00:09:00,321 --> 00:09:02,441
gets taken to them by a supply boat.

167
00:09:02,521 --> 00:09:06,441
The next delivery is in two days' time,
off the coast of Scotland.

168
00:09:06,881 --> 00:09:08,201
That's our chance!

169
00:09:09,561 --> 00:09:11,281
Yeah, that really has to stop.

170
00:09:14,121 --> 00:09:15,201
BILL: It's happening, Mum.

171
00:09:15,801 --> 00:09:17,681
I knew it would. So...

172
00:09:18,641 --> 00:09:21,201
Nardole has made contact
with the captain of the supply boat

173
00:09:21,281 --> 00:09:24,201
that runs to and from the prison ship
where the Doctor's being held.

174
00:09:24,841 --> 00:09:28,041
His son is serving
10 years in a lab our camp

175
00:09:28,121 --> 00:09:29,961
for possession of a box of comics.

176
00:09:31,121 --> 00:09:32,801
So he's no fan of the Monks.

177
00:09:34,321 --> 00:09:36,041
He'll get us on board the prison ship.

178
00:09:50,641 --> 00:09:52,521
Security is really tight obviously.

179
00:09:52,641 --> 00:09:55,121
But Nardole says there's not been much
in way of resistance

180
00:09:55,201 --> 00:09:57,201
since the Monks took over.
So they're more worried

181
00:09:57,281 --> 00:10:00,361
about the Doctor getting out
than anyone getting in.

182
00:10:05,481 --> 00:10:06,841
MAN: Get those crates moving.

183
00:10:12,801 --> 00:10:14,161
BILL: But what we don't want is for them

184
00:10:14,241 --> 00:10:16,481
to do a spot check
on our identity papers.

185
00:10:16,801 --> 00:10:17,801
Papers!

186
00:10:18,081 --> 00:10:19,081
Spot check.

187
00:10:19,761 --> 00:10:20,961
BILL: Mardole doesn't have any

188
00:10:21,041 --> 00:10:23,041
and I'm down as
university kitchen staff.

189
00:10:23,121 --> 00:10:24,121
MAN: Check!

190
00:10:41,561 --> 00:10:42,801
SOLDIER: (WHISPERING) It's them.

191
00:11:26,921 --> 00:11:28,321
(METAL DOOR CLANGS SHUT)

192
00:11:34,481 --> 00:11:37,441
All right, what you waiting for? We need
to get this stuff on board. Chop, chop.

193
00:11:38,081 --> 00:11:40,241
-MAN: Hold it. Back to work.
-Come on.

194
00:11:55,001 --> 00:11:56,921
BILL: After that we're on our own.

195
00:12:09,881 --> 00:12:12,001
(MEN TALKING INDISTINCTLY IN DISTANCE)

196
00:12:16,961 --> 00:12:18,761
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION CONTINUES)

197
00:12:22,761 --> 00:12:23,801
(SOFTLY) Careful.

198
00:12:36,641 --> 00:12:37,681
Doctor.

199
00:12:41,921 --> 00:12:43,001
Doctor, it's me.

200
00:12:44,921 --> 00:12:46,001
Guards!

201
00:12:47,321 --> 00:12:48,401
(GUNS COCKING)

202
00:12:49,281 --> 00:12:50,641
What are you doing here?

203
00:12:51,241 --> 00:12:53,161
Well, what does it look like?
We've come to save you.

204
00:12:53,321 --> 00:12:54,321
This is your doing, isn't it?

205
00:12:54,441 --> 00:12:55,601
You shouldn't be here.

206
00:12:55,681 --> 00:12:57,281
-I have to talk to the Monks now.
-Doctor...

207
00:12:57,361 --> 00:12:59,241
Stop. Don't. Don't move.
They will kill you.

208
00:12:59,521 --> 00:13:00,721
Stay where you are.

209
00:13:02,601 --> 00:13:03,601
(BEEPS)

210
00:13:03,961 --> 00:13:06,761
DOCTOR: Epsilon.
Fire. Jupiter. Lily.

211
00:13:10,241 --> 00:13:11,401
The Monks are on their way.

212
00:13:12,121 --> 00:13:13,561
When they get here,
let me do the talking.

213
00:13:14,881 --> 00:13:16,041
Wait. What was that?

214
00:13:16,961 --> 00:13:19,241
Did you actually just call them,
you nutter?

215
00:13:20,121 --> 00:13:21,721
You deserve an explanation.

216
00:13:22,081 --> 00:13:23,081
(GASPS)

217
00:13:25,721 --> 00:13:27,041
Human society's...

218
00:13:29,161 --> 00:13:30,161
Stagnating.

219
00:13:31,681 --> 00:13:33,321
You've stopped moving forward.

220
00:13:34,361 --> 00:13:35,681
In fact, you're regressing.

221
00:13:36,041 --> 00:13:38,561
-Well, this isn't exactly much better.
-It's safer.

222
00:13:38,641 --> 00:13:40,961
Not so much for the people
the Monks are killing.

223
00:13:41,241 --> 00:13:44,921
The Romans killed people and saved
billions more from disease.

224
00:13:46,001 --> 00:13:47,161
War, famine.

225
00:13:48,361 --> 00:13:49,361
And barbarism.

226
00:13:50,481 --> 00:13:51,481
No, wait.

227
00:13:53,641 --> 00:13:54,841
What about free will?

228
00:13:56,801 --> 00:13:57,801
You believe in free will.

229
00:13:58,641 --> 00:14:03,041
Your whole thing is... You made me write
a 3,000-word essay on free will.

230
00:14:03,121 --> 00:14:05,641
(CHUCKLES) Yes, well, I mean,
you had free will

231
00:14:05,721 --> 00:14:08,441
and look at what you did with it.
Worse than that, you had history.

232
00:14:09,241 --> 00:14:11,001
History was saying to you,

233
00:14:11,081 --> 00:14:13,241
"Look, I've got some examples
of fascism here for you to look at.

234
00:14:13,321 --> 00:14:15,561
"No? Fundamentalism?

235
00:14:15,961 --> 00:14:18,561
"No? Oh, okay. You carry on."”

236
00:14:19,161 --> 00:14:21,761
I had to stop you, or at least,
not stand in the way

237
00:14:21,841 --> 00:14:23,481
of someone else who wanted to.

238
00:14:23,561 --> 00:14:26,481
Because the guns were getting bigger,
the stakes were getting higher.

239
00:14:26,561 --> 00:14:29,161
And any minute now, it's gonna be
"Good night, Vienna."

240
00:14:29,241 --> 00:14:30,761
By the way,
you never delivered that essay.

241
00:14:30,841 --> 00:14:33,481
Because the world was invaded
by zombie Monks.

242
00:14:33,561 --> 00:14:35,041
And whose fault was that?

243
00:14:37,201 --> 00:14:38,961
Huh? I didn't ask for my sight back.

244
00:14:39,601 --> 00:14:42,561
No, you took it upon yourself
to ignore me.

245
00:14:42,641 --> 00:14:44,281
To do what you thought was best.

246
00:14:45,481 --> 00:14:47,441
All I can say is that we are lucky

247
00:14:47,521 --> 00:14:50,241
that it was a benevolent race
like the Monks, not the Daleks.

248
00:14:50,681 --> 00:14:52,881
Yes, I know the Monks are with us.
I get that.

249
00:14:52,961 --> 00:14:57,361
Yes, they play with history.
I'm not exactly thrilled about that.

250
00:14:57,441 --> 00:15:00,401
But they bring peace and order.

251
00:15:02,961 --> 00:15:03,961
Okay.

252
00:15:05,121 --> 00:15:06,681
Yeah, yeah, I get it. I...

253
00:15:06,761 --> 00:15:10,681
It's, it's like that time that we
discovered that huge fish creature

254
00:15:10,761 --> 00:15:12,481
in the Seine in Paris.

255
00:15:17,761 --> 00:15:19,561
That was a coded message.

256
00:15:20,921 --> 00:15:22,561
The big fish creature
was under the Thames.

257
00:15:24,121 --> 00:15:27,321
If I'd played along, she'd have known
that I was tricking her.

258
00:15:28,641 --> 00:15:29,641
Guns down.

259
00:15:31,961 --> 00:15:33,121
(DOCTOR SIGHS)

260
00:15:33,721 --> 00:15:35,521
I'm sorry, Bill. I just... I just...

261
00:15:36,681 --> 00:15:38,441
I really wanted to make you see.

262
00:15:44,281 --> 00:15:45,281
This...

263
00:15:47,481 --> 00:15:49,001
(VOICE FALTERING) This is real?

264
00:15:50,761 --> 00:15:53,281
You... You're actually...

265
00:15:54,121 --> 00:15:55,601
You're actually doing this.

266
00:15:59,121 --> 00:16:02,321
Do you have any idea

267
00:16:02,401 --> 00:16:04,361
how hard the past few months have been?

268
00:16:06,401 --> 00:16:09,041
How hard it's been
to hold on to the truth?

269
00:16:10,361 --> 00:16:14,161
It would have been so easy
(STAMMERS) to just give in

270
00:16:14,241 --> 00:16:16,161
and believe their lies.

271
00:16:17,121 --> 00:16:18,401
But I didn't.

272
00:16:20,961 --> 00:16:25,001
I fought against it. For you!

273
00:16:26,041 --> 00:16:27,881
For when you came back!

274
00:16:28,601 --> 00:16:30,361
And now you're saying
you've joined them.

275
00:16:33,001 --> 00:16:34,441
You're helping them.

276
00:16:46,401 --> 00:16:48,561
-Bill, put... Put the gun down.
-I'm serious, Doctor.

277
00:16:51,121 --> 00:16:52,881
We'll think of something else.

278
00:16:53,921 --> 00:16:56,721
But you better tell me now...

279
00:16:58,161 --> 00:17:01,481
Because if you help the Monks, then...

280
00:17:01,561 --> 00:17:03,081
Nothing will ever stop them.

281
00:17:03,641 --> 00:17:05,361
They'll be here forever.

282
00:17:06,841 --> 00:17:09,081
It's not a trick, it's not a plan.
I have joined the Monks.

283
00:17:10,361 --> 00:17:13,521
Whatever it takes, I'm gonna save you
from yourselves.

284
00:17:14,721 --> 00:17:15,721
(BREATH SHAKES)

285
00:17:18,121 --> 00:17:19,121
(GUNSHOTS)

286
00:17:49,481 --> 00:17:50,801
(SCREAMING)

287
00:17:55,481 --> 00:17:56,801
Good girl.

288
00:17:56,881 --> 00:17:58,121
(ALL LAUGHING)

289
00:18:02,601 --> 00:18:04,201
Regeneration a little bit too much?

290
00:18:04,281 --> 00:18:05,721
No, I thought it was a nice touch.

291
00:18:05,801 --> 00:18:08,761
Too much was Richard asking
for our identity papers.

292
00:18:08,841 --> 00:18:10,721
I couldn't resist it. Your face...

293
00:18:11,321 --> 00:18:12,601
Well, hello?

294
00:18:13,881 --> 00:18:15,721
Could somebody tell me
what the hell is going on?

295
00:18:15,801 --> 00:18:16,961
You did it.

296
00:18:17,201 --> 00:18:18,921
You did it.

297
00:18:20,641 --> 00:18:25,281
The Monks are using some kind of...
You know, something to control

298
00:18:25,361 --> 00:18:27,041
the population. They must be.

299
00:18:27,121 --> 00:18:30,201
Otherwise they wouldn't have been
able to hold on to power for this long.

300
00:18:30,321 --> 00:18:33,041
Now, they don't trust me yet,
not completely,

301
00:18:33,121 --> 00:18:36,321
and I had to just check that you weren't
under the influence, testing me.

302
00:18:36,561 --> 00:18:37,641
So you...

303
00:18:37,801 --> 00:18:40,441
(STAMMERS) You haven't turned,
you're not working for them?

304
00:18:41,361 --> 00:18:43,161
(ALL LAUGH)

305
00:18:43,441 --> 00:18:44,841
No, of course not.

306
00:18:45,641 --> 00:18:47,921
I spent the last six months planning

307
00:18:48,001 --> 00:18:50,441
and also recruiting all these chaps.

308
00:18:50,961 --> 00:18:56,041
De-programming them, one by one.
Talking some sense into them.

309
00:18:56,121 --> 00:18:58,281
And there's loads of them,
I could do with a Strepsil.

310
00:18:58,841 --> 00:18:59,921
But I shot you.

311
00:19:00,121 --> 00:19:02,121
Yes, well, that was the plan, you see?

312
00:19:02,201 --> 00:19:05,281
Everyone exchanged their ammo
for blanks.

313
00:19:06,081 --> 00:19:07,081
Did you forget, David?

314
00:19:07,961 --> 00:19:09,041
You forgot?

315
00:19:09,761 --> 00:19:11,841
Well, that would have really blown
the plan, wouldn't it?

316
00:19:12,521 --> 00:19:13,641
But you called the Monks.

317
00:19:14,001 --> 00:19:15,321
I called the kitchen. Oh...

318
00:19:15,401 --> 00:19:16,881
Could you pop down
and explain it to them?

319
00:19:16,961 --> 00:19:18,481
They're gonna be really confused.

320
00:19:18,601 --> 00:19:19,921
(INHALES DEEPLY)

321
00:19:22,641 --> 00:19:23,761
And you were in on this, too?

322
00:19:23,881 --> 00:19:25,361
DOCTOR: Oh, it was partly his idea.

323
00:19:25,841 --> 00:19:27,281
Oh, my...

324
00:19:28,401 --> 00:19:30,441
-God, I'm gonna beat the...
-DOCTOR: No, no, no...

325
00:19:30,561 --> 00:19:32,201
NARDOLE: She keeps hitting me.
She been doing it the...

326
00:19:32,281 --> 00:19:36,001
No, come on, come on.
We've got to band back together again.

327
00:19:36,841 --> 00:19:38,841
Now, lovely as it is

328
00:19:38,961 --> 00:19:41,441
to have you on board,
literally and metaphorically,

329
00:19:41,521 --> 00:19:42,761
we're going to need some help.

330
00:19:43,161 --> 00:19:44,601
So, who we gonna get?

331
00:19:44,761 --> 00:19:47,521
The only person I know
almost as smart as me.

332
00:19:49,961 --> 00:19:50,961
Oh!

333
00:19:52,361 --> 00:19:53,401
I see.

334
00:19:54,681 --> 00:19:57,201
Blimey. Has it really come to that?

335
00:20:04,881 --> 00:20:07,601
BILL: Mum, it's me. We're coming back.

336
00:20:18,161 --> 00:20:19,721
BILL: We could have snuck back in,

337
00:20:19,801 --> 00:20:21,641
but the Doctor being the Doctor...

338
00:20:24,281 --> 00:20:26,041
(SHIP HORN BLOWING)

339
00:20:34,161 --> 00:20:35,161
(LAUGHS)

340
00:20:40,601 --> 00:20:41,841
(CHURCH BELL TOLLING)

341
00:20:47,401 --> 00:20:48,521
MAN: Halt!

342
00:20:48,601 --> 00:20:50,641
BILL: By the time we got back
to the university,

343
00:20:50,841 --> 00:20:54,361
the Monks were waiting for us.
Of course.

344
00:20:56,161 --> 00:20:57,361
(BELL CONTINUES TOLLING)

345
00:20:57,561 --> 00:20:59,281
(MAN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY
IN DISTANCE)

346
00:20:59,641 --> 00:21:01,321
BILL: We weren't headed
to his office, though.

347
00:21:07,321 --> 00:21:10,801
Even so, the Doctor was nervous, Mum.
I could tell

348
00:21:11,241 --> 00:21:13,041
He had to do this, he said.

349
00:21:13,601 --> 00:21:15,401
He had to open the vault.

350
00:21:16,521 --> 00:21:18,161
(WHISPERS) Over to
the containment field, please!

351
00:21:21,241 --> 00:21:24,121
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

352
00:21:40,681 --> 00:21:42,001
(PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)

353
00:21:51,881 --> 00:21:52,881
BILL: This...

354
00:21:54,041 --> 00:21:55,561
This is just a woman.

355
00:21:57,281 --> 00:21:58,721
God, the way you and Nardole
have been carrying on

356
00:21:58,801 --> 00:22:00,681
I thought we had some kind of monster
in here or something.

357
00:22:00,801 --> 00:22:01,801
I do.

358
00:22:02,921 --> 00:22:05,321
Missy... Bill.

359
00:22:05,401 --> 00:22:08,161
Bill. Missy,
the other last of the Time Lords.

360
00:22:12,201 --> 00:22:13,521
Wait a sec.

361
00:22:13,601 --> 00:22:15,841
Why have you got a woman
locked in a vault?

362
00:22:15,921 --> 00:22:18,081
'Cause even I think that's weird
and I've been attacked by a puddle.

363
00:22:18,161 --> 00:22:20,401
She's going cold turkey from being bad.

364
00:22:20,481 --> 00:22:21,561
(CHUCKLES)

365
00:22:21,641 --> 00:22:24,081
I want to ask if you've had any dealings
with the Monks before.

366
00:22:24,161 --> 00:22:25,161
MISSY: Of course.

367
00:22:25,281 --> 00:22:26,601
I've had adventures, too.

368
00:22:27,441 --> 00:22:29,961
My whole life doesn't revolve
around you, you know.

369
00:22:30,121 --> 00:22:31,121
Did you defeat them?

370
00:22:31,361 --> 00:22:32,361
I did.

371
00:22:32,881 --> 00:22:33,881
How?

372
00:22:34,321 --> 00:22:35,321
(SCOFFS)

373
00:22:37,641 --> 00:22:39,481
I've got some requests.

374
00:22:39,561 --> 00:22:40,761
I want some new books.

375
00:22:41,121 --> 00:22:43,721
Some toys. Like a particle accelerator,

376
00:22:44,041 --> 00:22:46,601
3D printer and a pony.

377
00:22:46,761 --> 00:22:50,521
I don't think that you really grasp
what's going on here.

378
00:22:51,721 --> 00:22:55,081
Nice people generally don't haggle
over the fate of a planet.

379
00:22:55,281 --> 00:22:58,201
I once built a gun out of leaves.

380
00:22:58,281 --> 00:23:00,481
Do you think I couldn't get through
a door if I wanted to?

381
00:23:01,841 --> 00:23:03,001
I'm here.

382
00:23:03,241 --> 00:23:05,641
All right? I'm engaging
in the process.

383
00:23:06,681 --> 00:23:07,681
Okay.

384
00:23:08,241 --> 00:23:10,561
Yeah, we can... We can
get those things for you.

385
00:23:10,921 --> 00:23:12,321
C'est super.

386
00:23:14,401 --> 00:23:15,681
(SIGHS) So.

387
00:23:17,001 --> 00:23:18,401
What have we got so far?

388
00:23:20,121 --> 00:23:22,401
They hold onto power by
targeting the part of the brain

389
00:23:22,481 --> 00:23:25,921
specifically to do with
memory and perception. Correct?

390
00:23:26,001 --> 00:23:27,641
-Right?
-Getting warm.

391
00:23:27,721 --> 00:23:29,041
Fingers tingling.

392
00:23:29,641 --> 00:23:32,201
But they target it with what exactly?

393
00:23:32,721 --> 00:23:33,881
How do they sustain it?

394
00:23:34,081 --> 00:23:38,321
How do their lies infiltrate
the brains of billions?

395
00:23:38,721 --> 00:23:40,761
Is it some kind of
airborne psychoactive?

396
00:23:40,921 --> 00:23:42,801
No, no, no, no.
That's very cold, very cold.

397
00:23:42,881 --> 00:23:44,601
Something that's constantly

398
00:23:44,681 --> 00:23:46,441
being fed to the populace.

399
00:23:46,521 --> 00:23:49,081
Constantly consolidating its hold.
Is it in the water?

400
00:23:49,161 --> 00:23:51,201
God, no. It's freezing, freezing.

401
00:23:51,561 --> 00:23:53,481
Absolutely freezing.
Couldn't be colder.

402
00:23:53,801 --> 00:23:56,321
Very, very chilly. So, so chilly.
Oh, come on.

403
00:23:57,561 --> 00:23:59,281
I'm bored.

404
00:23:59,361 --> 00:24:01,041
You haven't been to see me
in six months.

405
00:24:01,121 --> 00:24:04,721
No one has, not even that bald bloke
who looks like an egg.

406
00:24:04,841 --> 00:24:06,521
What, you left her alone in here
for six months?

407
00:24:06,641 --> 00:24:08,161
I was in prison for six months.

408
00:24:08,361 --> 00:24:09,841
Start at the beginning.

409
00:24:10,401 --> 00:24:12,561
How do they get a foothold on a planet?

410
00:24:12,641 --> 00:24:14,521
Some idiot asks for their help.

411
00:24:14,601 --> 00:24:15,881
Well, not just any idiot.

412
00:24:15,961 --> 00:24:18,921
I mean, it has to be a properly
consenting human mind.

413
00:24:19,281 --> 00:24:20,601
A pure request.

414
00:24:20,721 --> 00:24:23,241
One without agenda or ulterior motive.

415
00:24:27,521 --> 00:24:28,681
It's them.

416
00:24:29,641 --> 00:24:31,761
That person creates a psychic link,

417
00:24:32,521 --> 00:24:34,841
which forms an anchor
that keeps the Monks in power.

418
00:24:34,921 --> 00:24:35,921
They are the lynchpin.

419
00:24:36,001 --> 00:24:37,201
Scalding, ow.

420
00:24:37,761 --> 00:24:40,161
But the brain waves of one person
wouldn't be powerful enough

421
00:24:40,681 --> 00:24:42,241
to contain an entire planet.

422
00:24:42,721 --> 00:24:44,241
The statues.

423
00:24:45,561 --> 00:24:48,201
As soon as they got here,
the Monks put up statues

424
00:24:49,201 --> 00:24:50,721
in every town square

425
00:24:50,801 --> 00:24:52,521
and every park, and every playground.

426
00:24:52,681 --> 00:24:54,601
You're on fire,
you're literally on fire,

427
00:24:54,681 --> 00:24:56,841
so caliente.
That's Spanish for "hot".

428
00:24:57,001 --> 00:24:58,521
The statues are transmitters.

429
00:24:59,401 --> 00:25:02,281
They boost the signal and beam it out
all around the world.

430
00:25:02,361 --> 00:25:03,921
Boom! You've exploded.

431
00:25:04,641 --> 00:25:05,681
Now all you have to do is

432
00:25:05,761 --> 00:25:08,481
find whoever opened to door
to the Monks in the first place.

433
00:25:08,721 --> 00:25:10,401
DOCTOR: Say I already have.
MISSY: Oh.

434
00:25:10,481 --> 00:25:11,921
Oh, well, then you are sorted.

435
00:25:12,201 --> 00:25:13,521
Just kill them.

436
00:25:14,001 --> 00:25:16,241
That weakens the Monks' grip
on the world.

437
00:25:20,601 --> 00:25:21,641
No, no.

438
00:25:21,721 --> 00:25:23,201
No, no, that can't right.

439
00:25:23,721 --> 00:25:26,121
There are planets that the Monks
have ruled for thousands of years.

440
00:25:26,201 --> 00:25:27,801
It's passed on through the bloodline.

441
00:25:28,881 --> 00:25:31,561
Usually the lynchpin goes on
to lead a normal life,

442
00:25:31,641 --> 00:25:34,961
have their own family, and the link
is passed down through the generations.

443
00:25:35,081 --> 00:25:37,841
But the Monks must have worked that out.
They've been doing this for millennia.

444
00:25:37,921 --> 00:25:40,761
Why? I mean, if the link is passed on,

445
00:25:40,961 --> 00:25:42,321
then the Monks stay in charge.

446
00:25:42,401 --> 00:25:45,161
Through, they think,
ruthlessness and efficiency.

447
00:25:45,801 --> 00:25:47,521
But if the lynchpin dies

448
00:25:47,641 --> 00:25:50,721
and the link isn't passed on
and the Monks get booted off the planet,

449
00:25:50,801 --> 00:25:53,081
well, they just chalk it up
to experience.

450
00:25:54,241 --> 00:25:56,401
(MISSY PLAYING THE PIANO)

451
00:25:59,601 --> 00:26:00,921
No, it's okay.

452
00:26:02,921 --> 00:26:04,681
-I want to speak to her.
-Yes.

453
00:26:05,081 --> 00:26:07,321
So, when you defeated
the Monks, that's how you did it.

454
00:26:07,881 --> 00:26:11,201
Well, at this point, all that was left
of the bloodline was a wee girl.

455
00:26:11,761 --> 00:26:14,081
And I just pushed her into a volcano.

456
00:26:15,441 --> 00:26:16,681
It's me.

457
00:26:17,361 --> 00:26:18,481
The lynchpin is me.

458
00:26:18,561 --> 00:26:19,601
(MISSY PLAYING THE PIANO)

459
00:26:19,681 --> 00:26:21,241
(SING-SONG) Awkward.

460
00:26:22,761 --> 00:26:24,041
So you are saying I have to die?

461
00:26:24,121 --> 00:26:25,481
No, if you were just to die,

462
00:26:25,601 --> 00:26:28,161
then everyone's false memories
would have to fade,

463
00:26:28,241 --> 00:26:29,361
and that could take ages.

464
00:26:29,601 --> 00:26:32,001
It's actually better
if you keep breathing,

465
00:26:32,121 --> 00:26:33,761
if your brain just keeps transmitting,

466
00:26:34,041 --> 00:26:35,681
well, nothing.

467
00:26:35,881 --> 00:26:38,721
That would blot out the residue
false memories.

468
00:26:38,801 --> 00:26:40,281
What would be left of me?

469
00:26:40,481 --> 00:26:41,801
You'd be a husk.

470
00:26:42,081 --> 00:26:44,761
Completely and irrevocably brain dead.

471
00:26:44,921 --> 00:26:47,681
You couldn't even get on
Celebrity Love Island.

472
00:26:48,921 --> 00:26:51,121
Even if that was the truth,
the fact that you're suggesting it shows

473
00:26:51,201 --> 00:26:52,521
that there's been no change.

474
00:26:52,961 --> 00:26:54,441
No, no point.

475
00:26:55,441 --> 00:26:57,321
We don't sacrifice people, it's wrong.

476
00:26:58,361 --> 00:26:59,801
Because it's easy.

477
00:27:00,081 --> 00:27:03,081
You know, back in the day,
I'd burn an entire city to the ground

478
00:27:03,161 --> 00:27:05,401
just to see the pretty shapes
the smoke made.

479
00:27:06,121 --> 00:27:08,641
I'm sorry your plus one
doesn't get a happy ending.

480
00:27:09,281 --> 00:27:14,521
But like it or not, I just saved
this world because I want to change it.

481
00:27:15,961 --> 00:27:18,801
Your version of good is not absolute.

482
00:27:19,641 --> 00:27:22,201
It's vain, arrogant, sentimental.

483
00:27:24,241 --> 00:27:26,441
But if you are waiting for me
to become all that

484
00:27:27,961 --> 00:27:30,761
I'm going to be here
for a long time yet.

485
00:27:36,681 --> 00:27:37,681
(HELICOPTER HOVERING)

486
00:27:41,561 --> 00:27:42,601
What did she say?

487
00:27:42,681 --> 00:27:44,721
-Nothing.
-There's a way to defeat them.

488
00:27:44,921 --> 00:27:46,721
DOCTOR: There is.
Well, there is, but not that.

489
00:27:46,881 --> 00:27:48,241
BILL: Come on.

490
00:27:48,921 --> 00:27:51,241
You knew she was gonna say
something like this.

491
00:27:51,761 --> 00:27:52,881
That's why you needed me back.

492
00:27:52,961 --> 00:27:53,961
(JETS DRONING)

493
00:27:54,041 --> 00:27:55,561
You could've escaped from that ship.

494
00:27:56,121 --> 00:27:58,841
You could've started something
to defeat the Monks without me.

495
00:27:59,081 --> 00:28:02,801
I wanted you back by my side because
it's the safest place in the world.

496
00:28:03,081 --> 00:28:04,601
NARDOLE: Can someone...
What did she say?

497
00:28:04,681 --> 00:28:05,881
She said it's me.

498
00:28:07,281 --> 00:28:09,921
I asked the Monks for help,
started all of this.

499
00:28:11,401 --> 00:28:12,921
So I have to be the one to finish it.

500
00:28:14,161 --> 00:28:18,041
The only downside is if
that's what we do...

501
00:28:19,321 --> 00:28:21,961
Well, it's not worth me starting
any long books.

502
00:28:22,041 --> 00:28:24,521
Okay, we'll let's,

503
00:28:24,601 --> 00:28:26,961
uh, put a pin in it for now,

504
00:28:27,481 --> 00:28:29,841
as they say, and

505
00:28:29,921 --> 00:28:32,321
see if we can think of something else.

506
00:28:33,521 --> 00:28:35,521
You said the safest place for me
was by your side.

507
00:28:36,361 --> 00:28:38,401
That's what's protecting the Monks.

508
00:28:39,521 --> 00:28:41,441
It's why their plan works.

509
00:28:41,561 --> 00:28:43,361
(HELICOPTER HOVERING)

510
00:28:52,881 --> 00:28:54,721
DOCTOR: The cathedral,
the Monks' headquarters.

511
00:28:55,521 --> 00:28:56,721
Oh, yes.

512
00:28:58,241 --> 00:28:59,521
We're gonna have to break in there.

513
00:29:00,361 --> 00:29:01,521
Why?

514
00:29:02,241 --> 00:29:06,761
Somewhere in there, the Monks
must have some kind of a machine

515
00:29:06,841 --> 00:29:09,601
that creates and broadcasts the myths
of their history.

516
00:29:10,161 --> 00:29:12,961
The ones that are powered by,
carried by, fed by

517
00:29:13,601 --> 00:29:14,881
your brainwaves.

518
00:29:15,241 --> 00:29:18,601
So, we get in, I plug myself into it,

519
00:29:19,001 --> 00:29:22,561
and replace the signals that
they are receiving with my brainwaves

520
00:29:22,641 --> 00:29:26,681
and beam out the true history
of the world.

521
00:29:27,041 --> 00:29:28,401
Oh-ho, yes.

522
00:29:28,561 --> 00:29:29,961
I can even throw in some other stuff.

523
00:29:30,041 --> 00:29:32,081
The things that I could change
just by thinking.

524
00:29:32,161 --> 00:29:34,961
Racism, people who talk in cinemas.

525
00:29:35,041 --> 00:29:39,801
Are you sure? This will be
an incredibly sophisticated transmitter,

526
00:29:39,881 --> 00:29:42,441
powerful enough to beam
highly detailed propaganda

527
00:29:42,521 --> 00:29:44,881
to the entire world 24 hours a day,

528
00:29:44,961 --> 00:29:47,961
and you're gonna
plug your brain into it?

529
00:29:48,241 --> 00:29:51,121
I know, it doesn't stand a chance.

530
00:30:04,961 --> 00:30:08,081
NARDOLE: That's odd. There's no Monks
guarding the entrance.

531
00:30:08,201 --> 00:30:09,641
Come away from the window.

532
00:30:10,441 --> 00:30:11,641
How many Monks were there?

533
00:30:11,721 --> 00:30:13,121
Oh, about 12 Monks in there.

534
00:30:13,521 --> 00:30:14,641
DOCTOR: Twelve?

535
00:30:21,321 --> 00:30:23,161
Well, you have to admit
that is ever so clever.

536
00:30:23,321 --> 00:30:24,641
You see?

537
00:30:24,761 --> 00:30:28,241
Another way they hang onto power
is to create a myth

538
00:30:28,321 --> 00:30:31,201
that they're here in greater numbers
than they really are.

539
00:30:31,561 --> 00:30:33,321
Beam's stronger here, isn't it?

540
00:30:34,201 --> 00:30:35,521
You can almost hear it.

541
00:30:36,241 --> 00:30:39,161
So hard to hang onto any thought of life
before the Monks.

542
00:30:40,001 --> 00:30:42,281
Yes, and it's going to get stronger

543
00:30:42,401 --> 00:30:44,121
the closer we get to the transmitter.

544
00:30:44,561 --> 00:30:47,081
The lies are gonna become
more convincing.

545
00:30:47,761 --> 00:30:49,081
You'll want to turn around.

546
00:30:49,361 --> 00:30:51,121
You won't know what you're doing here,

547
00:30:51,761 --> 00:30:54,401
or why you are working
against the Monks.

548
00:30:55,441 --> 00:30:59,561
Now, have you all got your
stereo headphone, eye thing?

549
00:30:59,641 --> 00:31:02,521
Yeah. You never told us
what we needed these for.

550
00:31:02,681 --> 00:31:04,041
Ah, this is where you come in.

551
00:31:16,761 --> 00:31:18,161
(SIRENS WAILING)

552
00:31:20,681 --> 00:31:22,801
BILL: 7he Monks are not our friends.

553
00:31:22,881 --> 00:31:26,641
They have invaded Earth
and made its people slaves.

554
00:31:26,721 --> 00:31:29,401
They cling on to power by means
of a powerful transmitter

555
00:31:29,481 --> 00:31:33,281
broadcasting myths and lies
that suggest they have always been here.

556
00:31:35,441 --> 00:31:38,321
In fact, they have only been here
a few months

557
00:31:38,401 --> 00:31:40,961
and have falsified and manipulated
our history.

558
00:31:42,241 --> 00:31:44,401
Our mission
is to interrupt their broadcast

559
00:31:44,481 --> 00:31:46,881
and replace it
with the true history of Earth,

560
00:31:46,961 --> 00:31:50,441
which will weaken
and undermine the Monks' power.

561
00:31:51,161 --> 00:31:53,241
The Monks are not our friends.

562
00:31:53,321 --> 00:31:56,721
They have invaded Earth
and made its people slaves.

563
00:31:56,801 --> 00:31:59,361
They cling on to power by means
of a powerful transmitter

564
00:31:59,441 --> 00:32:03,081
broadcasting myths and lies
that suggest they have always been here.

565
00:32:04,081 --> 00:32:05,401
BILL: In fact...
DOCTOR: Take cover!

566
00:32:05,481 --> 00:32:07,081
BILL: ...they've only been here
a few months

567
00:32:07,161 --> 00:32:09,721
and have falsified and manipulated
our history.

568
00:32:10,521 --> 00:32:12,921
Our mission
is to interrupt their broadcast

569
00:32:13,001 --> 00:32:15,281
and replace it
with the true history of Earth,

570
00:32:15,361 --> 00:32:17,841
which will weaken
and undermine the Monks' power.

571
00:32:18,001 --> 00:32:20,161
The Monks are not our friends.

572
00:32:20,441 --> 00:32:21,721
They have invaded Earth...

573
00:32:21,801 --> 00:32:23,681
-(SCREAMING)
-(RECORDING STOPS)

574
00:32:26,561 --> 00:32:28,961
-(GUNS FIRING)
-(SCREAMS)

575
00:32:38,721 --> 00:32:40,641
Are you okay?

576
00:32:40,721 --> 00:32:41,921
-Yeah.
-Yeah?

577
00:32:42,001 --> 00:32:46,081
I think it's my... Oh, oh...
Doctor!

578
00:33:05,761 --> 00:33:06,961
It's in here.

579
00:33:07,321 --> 00:33:08,921
(GUN COCKING)

580
00:33:09,561 --> 00:33:11,041
Ooh.

581
00:33:12,081 --> 00:33:13,481
Everything all right, Alan?

582
00:33:14,001 --> 00:33:15,321
ALAN: You tricked us.

583
00:33:15,401 --> 00:33:17,561
You tried to make us believe
the Monks were invaders.

584
00:33:18,561 --> 00:33:19,801
How could you say that?

585
00:33:20,601 --> 00:33:22,001
They've always been here.

586
00:33:22,321 --> 00:33:24,761
-You know that.
-Uh-huh.

587
00:33:25,001 --> 00:33:27,441
Uh, oh, I see.

588
00:33:27,961 --> 00:33:29,361
The Monks are our friends.

589
00:33:30,001 --> 00:33:31,601
I won't let you hurt them.

590
00:33:32,361 --> 00:33:33,641
I'LL die first.

591
00:33:34,281 --> 00:33:35,641
I'll kill you first.

592
00:33:39,001 --> 00:33:40,001
(THUD)

593
00:33:41,881 --> 00:33:43,481
Tarovian neck pinch.

594
00:33:44,001 --> 00:33:47,281
Yeah, I studied their martial arts
for a while, actually.

595
00:33:47,681 --> 00:33:49,921
Yeah, reached a level of Brown Tabard.

596
00:33:50,001 --> 00:33:51,881
Yeah, can't do it
with this hand, though.

597
00:33:51,961 --> 00:33:54,721
Kind of bugs me. Course, this wasn't
my original hand, as you know.

598
00:33:55,041 --> 00:33:57,401
I won this in a game of...
Uh, yeah... Let's...

599
00:33:58,921 --> 00:34:00,201
Trek on.

600
00:34:00,281 --> 00:34:01,281
(WHIRRING)

601
00:34:11,481 --> 00:34:13,041
DOCTOR: Fake news central.

602
00:34:29,241 --> 00:34:31,681
(TRANSMITTER TRILLING)

603
00:34:36,601 --> 00:34:38,201
(BEEPING)

604
00:34:38,961 --> 00:34:40,601
I can think.

605
00:34:42,401 --> 00:34:43,481
They're not in my head, why is that?

606
00:34:44,721 --> 00:34:46,521
We're in the eye of the storm.

607
00:34:47,961 --> 00:34:49,081
Guard the doors.

608
00:34:49,201 --> 00:34:50,361
I can't be interrupted.

609
00:35:15,401 --> 00:35:16,681
Boo!

610
00:35:18,081 --> 00:35:19,401
Not necessary.

611
00:35:20,161 --> 00:35:21,161
(VOCALISING)

612
00:35:23,441 --> 00:35:25,001
DOCTOR: Okay, he's out.
Let's do this.

613
00:35:41,521 --> 00:35:42,841
(WHIRRING)

614
00:35:50,081 --> 00:35:52,641
It's working.
The Monks are disappearing.

615
00:35:52,841 --> 00:35:53,841
(GASPS)

616
00:35:54,561 --> 00:35:55,761
Oh, I didn't agree to this.

617
00:35:56,121 --> 00:35:57,561
What's happening?

618
00:35:57,641 --> 00:36:00,001
It's fighting back. It's blocking me.

619
00:36:00,081 --> 00:36:01,481
Countering every move.

620
00:36:03,001 --> 00:36:04,001
(WHIRRING)

621
00:36:07,161 --> 00:36:09,041
(POWERING UP)

622
00:36:10,081 --> 00:36:11,081
(GROANS)

623
00:36:11,201 --> 00:36:12,641
NARDOLE: Look.

624
00:36:15,081 --> 00:36:16,641
Oh, no, no, no.

625
00:36:21,001 --> 00:36:22,481
(DOCTOR STRAINING)

626
00:36:26,081 --> 00:36:27,441
(DOCTOR SCREAMS)

627
00:36:27,561 --> 00:36:28,881
Doctor!

628
00:36:38,241 --> 00:36:39,441
(GASPS)

629
00:36:42,041 --> 00:36:43,961
I wanted to do it before you woke up.

630
00:36:45,441 --> 00:36:46,521
But I had to say goodbye.

631
00:36:47,201 --> 00:36:51,281
Bill, whatever you're planning,
there's no need for this.

632
00:36:51,441 --> 00:36:53,921
Let me try again.
He caught me unawares.

633
00:36:54,041 --> 00:36:55,361
Cup of tea, I'll get my second wind.

634
00:36:55,481 --> 00:36:58,481
Even your brain couldn't stand
another roasting like that.

635
00:36:58,561 --> 00:37:00,321
So we'll find another way.
Let me talk to Missy again.

636
00:37:00,441 --> 00:37:03,281
We have the answer, Doctor, please.

637
00:37:03,641 --> 00:37:05,961
I don't want our last conversation
to be this.

638
00:37:06,041 --> 00:37:08,241
I don't want this to be
our last conversation.

639
00:37:15,601 --> 00:37:17,241
Well, goodbye, Doctor.

640
00:37:25,721 --> 00:37:26,841
Thank you.

641
00:37:29,961 --> 00:37:31,241
God, it was worth it.

642
00:37:39,521 --> 00:37:40,521
Bill...

643
00:37:41,721 --> 00:37:44,241
Bill, no don't. Bill, Bill, Bill...

644
00:37:44,561 --> 00:37:46,001
Bill, it will kill you. Bill...

645
00:37:46,481 --> 00:37:47,561
It's too powerful...

646
00:37:48,001 --> 00:37:49,721
Bill, I... I order you!

647
00:37:50,561 --> 00:37:52,601
I'm ordering you not to do this, Bill!

648
00:37:53,001 --> 00:37:54,281
Nardole, untie me!

649
00:37:54,521 --> 00:37:55,641
(STRAINING)

650
00:37:56,281 --> 00:37:57,321
(DOCTOR GRUNTS)

651
00:37:58,121 --> 00:37:59,441
Nardole, untie me now!

652
00:37:59,521 --> 00:38:00,921
Bill, don't do this.

653
00:38:01,081 --> 00:38:02,481
(EXHALES) Okay...

654
00:38:03,001 --> 00:38:04,361
(INHALES SHARPLY)

655
00:38:06,681 --> 00:38:09,441
I don't usually let someone
erase my brain on the first date, but

656
00:38:10,481 --> 00:38:12,001
seeing as it's you...

657
00:38:13,281 --> 00:38:14,681
(STRAINING) Argh! Ugh!

658
00:38:15,441 --> 00:38:16,721
Ahh...

659
00:38:18,481 --> 00:38:19,961
(WHIRRING)

660
00:38:20,481 --> 00:38:21,521
(GASPS)

661
00:38:25,361 --> 00:38:26,681
(GASPS)

662
00:38:33,361 --> 00:38:34,721
Oh, no...

663
00:38:37,001 --> 00:38:39,721
No, no... No, no, no!

664
00:38:40,721 --> 00:38:42,201
They're hijacking her memories.

665
00:38:43,201 --> 00:38:45,521
Infecting them like a virus.

666
00:38:45,761 --> 00:38:47,441
Just reinforcing the lies.

667
00:38:48,721 --> 00:38:50,321
She's died for nothing.

668
00:38:52,121 --> 00:38:53,521
(STRAINING)

669
00:38:54,041 --> 00:38:55,041
(GRUNTS)

670
00:38:55,121 --> 00:38:57,401
Come on, there must be a way
to shut this thing down!

671
00:39:08,121 --> 00:39:09,321
Hello, Mum.

672
00:39:12,921 --> 00:39:14,081
Doctor, look.

673
00:39:17,561 --> 00:39:19,561
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

674
00:39:25,641 --> 00:39:29,321
You clever, brilliant, ridiculous girl.

675
00:39:29,401 --> 00:39:30,441
Look at that.

676
00:39:30,521 --> 00:39:32,121
All the pictures I gave you.

677
00:39:32,201 --> 00:39:34,881
I thought I was just being kind
but I was saving the world.

678
00:39:34,961 --> 00:39:37,001
Bill, if there's
any of you left in there, listen.

679
00:39:37,121 --> 00:39:38,161
(GASPS)

680
00:39:38,241 --> 00:39:40,121
You have to keep thinking
about your mum,

681
00:39:40,201 --> 00:39:41,401
the memory you created.

682
00:39:42,001 --> 00:39:45,001
Her voice, her smile,
the Monks can't get near it.

683
00:39:45,081 --> 00:39:46,681
(MONK GROANING)

684
00:39:47,361 --> 00:39:49,041
Fill your mind with it.

685
00:39:49,601 --> 00:39:50,961
Push it into every corner.

686
00:39:53,601 --> 00:39:54,641
Bill!

687
00:39:55,721 --> 00:39:56,921
Mum.

688
00:39:58,121 --> 00:39:59,201
She's filling its mind

689
00:39:59,281 --> 00:40:03,561
with one pure, uncorrupted,
irresistible image.

690
00:40:04,161 --> 00:40:07,041
Now it's broadcasting it to the world
because it can't help it.

691
00:40:07,921 --> 00:40:10,321
All those years
you kept it alive inside you.

692
00:40:10,441 --> 00:40:13,281
An isolated subroutine in a living mind.

693
00:40:14,601 --> 00:40:16,881
Perfect. Untouchable.

694
00:40:18,561 --> 00:40:21,401
She's a window on the world
without the Monks.

695
00:40:23,521 --> 00:40:27,001
Absolutely loved, absolutely trusted.

696
00:40:28,041 --> 00:40:32,321
And that window is opening everywhere.

697
00:40:33,001 --> 00:40:35,161
A glimpse of freedom.

698
00:40:36,921 --> 00:40:41,081
But a glimpse is all you need.

699
00:40:41,681 --> 00:40:44,241
The lie is breaking.

700
00:40:45,841 --> 00:40:49,081
Bill's mum, you just went viral.

701
00:41:01,241 --> 00:41:03,121
DOCTOR: You did it,
you broke the signal.

702
00:41:03,201 --> 00:41:04,601
NARDOLE: What are the Monks gonna do?

703
00:41:04,921 --> 00:41:08,401
What oppressors always do
when they realise who's really in power.

704
00:41:09,721 --> 00:41:10,881
They run.

705
00:41:12,241 --> 00:41:14,041
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

706
00:41:24,521 --> 00:41:26,161
(BEEPS)

707
00:41:26,321 --> 00:41:27,681
BILL: This is exciting, isn't it?

708
00:41:28,321 --> 00:41:30,361
You know, kind of,
it's like a turning point.

709
00:41:30,921 --> 00:41:33,161
Humans have learnt that
they can overthrow dictators

710
00:41:33,241 --> 00:41:34,281
and stuff, they just...

711
00:41:34,521 --> 00:41:35,681
They just have to band together.

712
00:41:35,761 --> 00:41:37,441
Well, it's not quite as simple as that.

713
00:41:38,241 --> 00:41:40,121
You, appalling hair.

714
00:41:40,601 --> 00:41:42,681
This thing that we are sitting on,
what is it?

715
00:41:42,841 --> 00:41:46,521
Uh, we thought they were just like
filming something here or something.

716
00:41:46,601 --> 00:41:49,601
Thank you, very helpful,
now go away or something.

717
00:41:51,841 --> 00:41:54,681
You see?
The Monks have erased themselves.

718
00:41:55,401 --> 00:41:58,561
Humanity is doomed to never learn
from its mistakes.

719
00:42:00,921 --> 00:42:04,401
Well, I guess that's part of our charm.

720
00:42:04,841 --> 00:42:07,041
No, it's really quite annoying.

721
00:42:09,121 --> 00:42:10,561
Anyway, I mustn't keep you.

722
00:42:11,601 --> 00:42:13,041
Three thousand words

723
00:42:14,041 --> 00:42:17,881
on the mechanics of free will,
now six months overdue.

724
00:42:17,961 --> 00:42:19,001
(GASPS)

725
00:42:21,161 --> 00:42:22,761
Why do you put up with us, then?

726
00:42:24,841 --> 00:42:26,241
In amongst seven billion,

727
00:42:27,641 --> 00:42:28,841
there's someone like you.

728
00:42:32,521 --> 00:42:34,641
That's why I put up
with the rest of them.

729
00:42:57,841 --> 00:42:59,881
I keep remembering
all the people I've killed.

730
00:43:03,361 --> 00:43:04,761
Every day I think of more.

731
00:43:06,881 --> 00:43:08,081
Being bad.

732
00:43:09,561 --> 00:43:11,081
Being bad drowned that out.

733
00:43:14,241 --> 00:43:16,481
I didn't know I even knew their names.

734
00:43:20,521 --> 00:43:22,561
You didn't tell me about this bit.

735
00:43:24,161 --> 00:43:26,041
I'm sorry, but this is good.

736
00:43:27,841 --> 00:43:29,241
(SNIFFLING)

737
00:43:29,841 --> 00:43:31,001
Okay.

738
00:43:38,121 --> 00:43:40,321
BILL: 7here were humans on Mars
in Victorian times?

739
00:43:40,401 --> 00:43:42,201
DOCTOR: No, there weren't.

740
00:43:42,561 --> 00:43:43,841
MAN: Friday asked for my help.

741
00:43:43,921 --> 00:43:45,281
In return for what?

742
00:43:45,441 --> 00:43:46,481
Halt!

743
00:43:46,841 --> 00:43:49,441
This could be the entrance
to an Ice Warrior hive.

744
00:43:49,521 --> 00:43:51,241
DOCTOR: Friday has been
using you all along.

745
00:43:52,681 --> 00:43:55,801
His aim is to get back to Mars
and find his queen.

746
00:43:55,921 --> 00:43:58,681
Rise, my Ice Warriors.

747
00:43:58,761 --> 00:44:00,641
Rise!

748
00:44:00,881 --> 00:44:03,041
I daresay the British army
is more than a match

749
00:44:03,121 --> 00:44:05,161
for a bunch of upright crocodiles.

750
00:44:05,841 --> 00:44:07,961
You don't stand a chance against
the Ice Warriors.

751
00:44:09,161 --> 00:44:11,601
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

